docs.lead_paragraph: DEATH OF JAMES H. COLLINS, ESQ.--Our community was shocked on Saturday morning, by the announcement of the sudden and unexpected death of JAMES H. COLLINS, Esq. This distressing event occurred on Saturday morning at 6 o'-clock. Mr. COLLINS was in his usual good health and vigor, attending the Supreme Court now sitting at Ottowa.

headline.main: Execution of Jennings at New Haven.

docs.lead_paragraph: [The following letter, though its receipt has been accidentally delayed, will be read with interest:] NEW-HAVEN, Monday, July 10, 1854. This morning, between 10 and 11 o'clock, MICHAEL J. JENNINGS was executed in the jail-yard, for the murder of Mrs. BRADLEY, of North Haven, about a year ago.

docs.lead_paragraph: Rumor is thousand-tongued, and all her tongues are busy telling large stories of Cholera. We cannot agree with the Commissioners of Health, that the best way for those who are informed, is to attend to their business simply and say nothing.

docs.lead_paragraph: M. M. HOWES, of New-Milford, who was sent to State Prison for ten years, on a charge of attempting to kill a school mistress in his neighborhood, died in the prison at Weathersfield on Sunday afternoon last. He had been confined about two years. HOWES was a mild inoffensive young man, about 21 years of age at the time of his sentence.

headline.main: The fifth Ward and the Cholera.

docs.lead_paragraph: An indignation meeting of citizens of the Fifth Ward was held last evening. Earnest remonstrances were uttered against the occupation of the Emigration Office, in Franklin-street, for the purposes of the Cholera Hospital.
